Thanks for the response.  The only thing that changes between my tests is the DB URL (string).  Having to maintain a subclass for each db AND a test suite listing all of the subclasses seems onerous.  It seems like I should be able to simply give a list of DB URLs and have JUnit execute a setup method ONCE for each set of tests.  What&#39;s the easiest way to do this?

----- Original Message ----
From: jason r tibbetts &lt;tibbettj@...&gt;
To: junit@yahoogroups.com
Sent: Thursday, June 7, 2007 5:46:35 PM
Subject: Re: [junit] Class-level Parameterized Test













            Ed,



&gt; I have a set of tests in a single Unit, say test1() and test2(). I

&gt; want to execute my set of tests over the elements in a list of

&gt; resources where each resource is expensive to allocate. For example,

&gt; let&#39;s say I had a list of databases (e.g., OracleDB, MySQLDB, ...),

&gt; and I want to execute my set of tests over each DB. Creating a DB

&gt; connection is expensive so I only want to create one DB connection per

&gt; test set as follows:

&gt; 

&gt; Create OracleDB connection

&gt; test1()

&gt; test2()

&gt; Create MySQLDB connection

&gt; test1()

&gt; test2()

&gt; 

&gt; What&#39;s the best way to do this? I know about parameterized JUnit

&gt; tests; however, this calls the constructor for EACH test. I only want

&gt; to allocate a DB connection per test set. Perhaps there&#39;s some

&gt; @BeforeParameter hook that is only executed when the parameter values

&gt; changes, not for each test.



Sounds like what you want isn&#39;t a parameterized test, but a test 

fixture. Create an abstract base class for the test methods, and give it 

a getConnection( ) abstract method. Then subclass it, once per DB, and in 

each subclass, use @BeforeClass and @AfterClass to do the expensive 

stuff. Each subclass&#39;s getConnection( ) will return its (static) connection.














